83rd OREGON LEGISLATIVE ASSEMBLY--2026 Regular Session
HOUSE AMENDMENTS TO
HOUSE BILL 4177
By COMMITTEE ON RULES
February 23
1 On page 1 of the printed bill, line 2, after “192.630,” insert “192.640, 192.650,”.
2 On page 2, line 22, delete “governing body may not” and insert “public body may not permit a
3 governing body to”.
4 On page 3, after line 13, insert:
5 “SECTION 3. ORS 192.640 is amended to read:
6 “192.640. (1) [The governing body of] A public body shall provide for and give public notice,
7 reasonably calculated to give actual notice to interested persons including news media which have
8 requested notice, of the time and place for holding regular meetings of each of its governing
9 bodies. The notice shall also include a list of the principal subjects anticipated to be considered at
10 the meeting, but this requirement shall not limit the ability of a governing body to consider addi-
11 tional subjects.
12 “(2) If an executive session only will be held, the notice shall be given to the members of the
13 governing body, to the general public and to news media which have requested notice, stating the
14 specific provision of law authorizing the executive session.
15 “(3) No special meeting shall be held without at least 24 hours’ notice to the members of the
16 governing body, the news media which have requested notice and the general public. In case of an
17 actual emergency, a meeting may be held upon such notice as is appropriate to the circumstances,
18 but the minutes for such a meeting shall describe the emergency justifying less than 24 hours’ no-
19 tice.
20 “SECTION 4. ORS 192.650 is amended to read:
21 “192.650. (1) [The governing body of] A public body shall provide for the sound, video or digital
22 recording or the taking of written minutes of all [its] meetings for each of its governing bodies.
23 Neither a full transcript nor a full recording of the meeting is required, except as otherwise pro-
24 vided by law, but the written minutes or recording must give a true reflection of the matters dis-
25 cussed at the meeting and the views of the participants. All minutes or recordings shall be available
26 to the public within a reasonable time after the meeting, and shall include at least the following
27 information:
28 “(a) All members of the governing body present;
29 “(b) All motions, proposals, resolutions, orders, ordinances and measures proposed and their
30 disposition;
31 “(c) The results of all votes and, except for public bodies consisting of more than 25 members
32 unless requested by a member of that body, the vote of each member by name;
33 “(d) The substance of any discussion on any matter; and
34 “(e) Subject to ORS 192.311 to 192.478 relating to public records, a reference to any document
35 discussed at the meeting.
LC 118/HB 4177-2

1 “(2) Minutes of executive sessions shall be kept in accordance with subsection (1) of this section.
2 However, the minutes of a hearing held under ORS 332.061 shall contain only the material not ex-
3 cluded under ORS 332.061 (2). Instead of written minutes, a record of any executive session may be
4 kept in the form of a sound or video tape or digital recording, which need not be transcribed unless
5 otherwise provided by law. If the disclosure of certain material is inconsistent with the purpose for
6 which a meeting under ORS 192.660 is authorized to be held, that material may be excluded from
7 disclosure. However, excluded materials are authorized to be examined privately by a court in any
8 legal action and the court shall determine their admissibility.
9 “(3) A reference in minutes or a recording to a document discussed at a meeting of a governing
10 body of a public body does not affect the status of the document under ORS 192.311 to 192.478.
11 “(4) A public body may charge a person a fee under ORS 192.324 for the preparation of a tran-
12 script from a recording.”.
